Who Owns Your Research: A Survey

Jan Vitek

March 12, 2015

There were 819 responses with 54% of respondents being members of the ACM. Membership is higher in North America (74%) and lower in the rest of the world (49%). The majority of respondents is from Europe (52%) with the other biggest chunk being from the USA and Canada (37%). The geographic distribution is shown in the following pie chart.

The respondent are split between academia (79%) and industry (19%). Lastly, the relative seniority of respondents as measured by the time from their first publication is summarized in the following pie chart.

In the rest of this document we will use the following shortcuts: USA to mean responses from North America, EU for responses that come from Europe, Senior for respondent who have published their first paper more than 20 years ago, Middle for those who have first published ten years ago, and Junior for authors who have published less than 10 years ago. ACM will denote respondent who are members of the ACM.

Open Access is a Moral Imperative

On the question asking if open access (OA) was a moral imperative the vast majority of respondents agreed (73%). The other responses where a a desirable features and not essential. The proportion of respondents who believe that adopting OA is a necessity is different depending on origin and seniority. The following table shows the most significant differences. Respondents outside of the USA were slightly more favorable to OA (75%). Seniority seemed to play a big role in attitudes, with more junior respondents having stronger feelings (81%). The most striking difference is between Senior USA Academics and Junior USA Academics the former favoring OA at 53% and the latter at a whopping 87%.

In all groups the majority views open access as a moral imperative.

The question about how to fund OA divides respondents: 27% are in favor of author processing charges while 41% argue for increased conference registrations.

The remaining suggestions for funding OA are listed next. A number of comments suggest that a Green OA model shoud be considered. Other suggest models based on voluntary donnations similar to Wikipedia, on governmental and industry support, by increased ACM membership fees. Several comments point to arXiv as an example to follow. Lastly, some suggest cutting ACMs expenses.

In the case an author processing charge was selected, how much would be a reasonable price (in USD) for a paper? The following pie chart breaks the price down.

The majority of respondents, 63% to be precise, is willing to pay no more than $100 per paper. An additional 27% is willing to pay $200.

The issue of copyrights is fairly clear cut with 71% saying that leaving copyrights with the authors is essential.

The last question was wether it would be reasonable to look for another publisher if an open access option was not available within the ACM by 2017. The marhority of respondents, 71% was in favor of such a switch.

Looking closer reveals some interesting distinctions. The majority ACM members are in favor of looking for an open access publisher by 2017, as with the other results sentiments for OA are stronger in Europe.

The biggest difference in opinion is between the Senior USA ACM members who are almost evenly split (slight majority in favor) and the Junior respondents who are strongly in favor of doing what it takes to get OA.

## [240] The role used to be serving as a point of contact among researchers. That's an outdated role: we don't need ACM to play that role any more. We all can organize our own conferences and journals and web sites, thank you.\n\nACM should scale back and focus on the things that we cannot do well ourselves. For example, you could do a better job of helping us to sift through all the bijillions of papers published each year to find the ones that are most interesting and useful. In addition, you could help funding entities to more easily make sense of whether researchers are having a real impact on the world outside academia. And you could apply to NSF for grants of your own to boost efforts to translate research into teaching and practice.\n\nThink of it this way: academic research has uncovered lots of gems--ideas of great value to other scientists, to students, and to the world at large. I don't know of any organization currently focused on discovering those gems and getting them out to the people who need them most. ACM could be that organization.\n\nIn the meantime, from what I've seen so far, you have been overly focused on small ideas. You are worried about how you'll protect your market share from the rise of open publishing, how you'll compete. Think bigger. Your role is no longer to be a publisher and conference organizer. Your role is to develop a new business model as an intermediary that serves as a connection between research and impact.\n\nIf ACM isn't going to do it, then who is?

## [405] Legacy. To paraphrase Clay Shirky in "Here Comes Everybody" once an organization exists the organization itself becomes a higher priority than whatever it was originally supposed to do, in this case distribute scientific knowledge as widely as possible. Obviously the organization is currently in the way of that goal. The papers should be in the public domain so they can be distributed. Perpituity will take care of itself if you get out of the way.
